Artist Interruptus

The story of Portrait of the Art Dealer as a Young Man concludes, somewhat =
abruptly, in 1977, with Grace Jones taking the stage at Studio 54=E2=80=94t=
he moment, he says, when the =E2=80=9960s truly ended. When we spoke, Findl=
ay told me it was a deliberate choice to not include any details about what=
 happened to any of the book=E2=80=99s characters after that point. But tha=
t omission deprives us of a good example of what he wants us to understand.

To wit: One of the artists included in the first show Findlay mounted in So=
Ho, in October 1968=E2=80=94most likely the first gallery show ever in Soho=
=E2=80=94was John Baldessari, who had come to him with black-and-white phot=
ographs of his conceptual word paintings. Findlay sold some of the works by=
 the other artists in that first show, but no one bit on Baldessari. One of=
 his paintings sat
in Findlay=E2=80=99s office for months. =E2=80=9CI loved having that painti=
ng behind my desk for $1,200,=E2=80=9D he told me. (Or was it $800? He can=
=E2=80=99t remember.) But not selling it was not considered a failure. What=
 Findlay doesn=E2=80=99t say in the book is that 40 years later, the painti=
ng sold at auction for $4.4 million. I was in the auction room with Findlay=
 when that happened. He exited in high spirits, laughing. No gnashing resen=
tment, just genuine amusement.

