=80=99s larger point: the value of all art is social. =E2=80=9CI wanted to =
provide some navigation,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CI thought if I could=
 show people the zig-zaggy path that I took,=E2=80=9D they would understand=
 that there are other ways to engage with art than through money. (Not that=
 there=E2=80=99s anything wrong with the money; Findlay is an art dealer, a=
fter all.) The point here isn=E2=80=99t that Findlay spotted the value long=
 before others. It=E2=80=99s that one should
trust one=E2=80=99s own responses to art, which are far more valuable than =
any market returns one might achieve=E2=80=94or miss out on.

Findlay, in this book at least, is more interested in transporting us back =
to a particular moment in time, before the art world turned into a market. =
As an example, Findlay pointed to the collectors of the =E2=80=9960s and =
=E2=80=9970s who were just having fun buying art. =E2=80=9CThey weren=E2=80=
=99t spending huge sums of money for them,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CTh=
ey would go to galleries regularly and chat with dealers. They liked what t=
hey were buying even though there were plenty of people who thought it was =
risible.=E2=80=9D And he wants people to understand that you can have fun w=
ith it, too. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not rocket science,=E2=80=9D he said, =
=E2=80=9Cbut you have to look at a lot.=E2=80=9D He implores gallery goers =
to have confidence that their reactions to art=E2=80=94good or bad=E2=80=94=
are valid. =E2=80=9CAnd you have to do it yourself.=E2=80=9D

On Sunday, I=E2=80=99m hoping to have a look at another storied art dealer,=
 whose collection will be auctioned in Switzerland this September. The work=
s don=E2=80=99t look cheap by any means, but after the recent bout of infla=
tion, they might be priced for today=E2=80=99s market. At least, there shou=
ld be a lot of people watching to get a better sense of the Modern market w=
hen works by Kirchner, Klee, Giacometti, and other names all go up for sale=
=2E

Until then,
Marion

