          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The story of<i> Por=
trait of the Art Dealer as a Young Man </i>concludes, somewhat abruptly, in=
 1977, with <b>Grace Jones</b> taking the stage at Studio 54=E2=80=94the mo=
ment, he says, when the =E2=80=9960s truly ended. When we spoke, Findlay to=
ld me it was a deliberate choice to not include any details about what happ=
ened to any of the book=E2=80=99s characters after that point. But that omi=
ssion deprives us of a good example of what he wants us to understand. <br/=
><br/>To wit: One of the artists included in the first show Findlay mounted=
 in SoHo, in October 1968=E2=80=94most likely the first gallery show <i>eve=
r</i> in Soho=E2=80=94was <b>John</b> <b>Baldessari</b>, who had come to hi=
m with black-and-white photographs of his conceptual word paintings. Findla=
y sold some of the works by the other artists in that first show, but no on=
e bit on Baldessari. One of his paintings sat
in Findlay=E2=80=99s office for months. =E2=80=9CI loved having that painti=
ng behind my desk for $1,200,=E2=80=9D he told me. (Or was it $800? He can=
=E2=80=99t remember.) But not selling it was not considered a failure. What=
 Findlay doesn=E2=80=99t say in the book is that 40 years later, the painti=
ng sold at auction for $4.4 million. I was in the auction room with Findlay=
 when that happened. He exited in high spirits, laughing. No gnashing resen=
tment, just genuine amusement. <br/><br/>Of course, the reader doesn=E2=80=
=99t need this context to get Findlay=E2=80=99s larger point: the value of =
all art is social. =E2=80=9CI wanted to provide some navigation,=E2=80=9D h=
e told me. =E2=80=9CI thought if I could show people the zig-zaggy path tha=
t I took,=E2=80=9D they would understand that there are other ways to engag=
e with art than through money. (Not that there=E2=80=99s anything <i>wrong<=
/i> with the money; Findlay <i>is</i> an art dealer, after all.) The point =
here isn=E2=80=99t that Findlay spotted the value long before others. It=E2=
=80=99s that one should
trust one=E2=80=99s own responses to art, which are far more valuable than =
any market returns one might achieve=E2=80=94or miss out on. <br/><br/>Find=
lay, in this book at least, is more interested in transporting us back to a=
 particular moment in time, before the art world turned into a market. As a=
n example, Findlay pointed to the collectors of the =E2=80=9960s and =E2=80=
=9970s who were just having <i>fun</i> buying art. =E2=80=9CThey weren=E2=
=80=99t spending huge sums of money <i>for them</i>,=E2=80=9D he told me. =
=E2=80=9CThey would go to galleries regularly and chat with dealers. They l=
iked what they were buying even though there were plenty of people who thou=
ght it was risible.=E2=80=9D And he wants people to understand that you can=
 have fun with it, too. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not rocket science,=E2=80=9D =
he said, =E2=80=9Cbut you have to look at <i>a lot</i>.=E2=80=9D He implore=
s gallery goers to have confidence that their reactions to art=E2=80=94good=
 or bad=E2=80=94are valid. =E2=80=9CAnd you have to do it yourself.=E2=80=
=9D <br/></td>
